Elysian Capital II LP – Report of the Manager for the quarter ended 30 June 2018
For circulation to Limited Partners only
At 30 June 2018 the Fund had cumulatively drawn down £127.0 million, representing 50.8% of total
commitments.  The Fund is currently invested in 5 portfolio companies at a total cost of £109.3 million.  The new
investment in Key Travel was completed on 25 May 2018 with a cost of £27.5 million.  Taking the portfolio as a
whole the valuation of £123.5 million represents a 1.13 gross multiple uplift at 30 June 2018.
The table below summarises the quarter end valuations of the realised and unrealised fund investments
In January 2016, Elysian invested £11.8 million out of a total consideration of £26.7 million for 57.8% of Sambro
International Ltd. Barclays provided a senior debt facility of £4.0 million alongside roll-over and extending
existing working capital facilities.  The balance of the equity is held by senior management.
NOTES: Actual Net debt includes £2.1m of cash, £3.0m of ID loans, £5.8m of trade import loans and £3.4m senior loan
Trading in Q2 continued to be challenging with the retail sector as a whole experiencing difficulties and several
large retailers struggling, particularly in the UK.  This has been exaggerated by a non-licensed toy range (LOL)
taking a material share of wallet. As a result sales declined to £14.0 million in the quarter compared to £18.9
million in the same period last year.  Whilst gross margins were broadly maintained, EBITDA was adversely
impacted by the investments in sales focused headcount.
Elysian Capital II LP – Report of the Manager for the quarter ended 30 June 2018
For circulation to Limited Partners only
Encouragingly the order book in June is £38.6 million, which is 14% higher than the order book of £33.8 million
at the same time last year.  The most recent forecast suggests a flat full year-on-year sales outturn reflecting a
turnaround in the second half of this year.  Management has used a disciplined ‘Bridge the Gap’ plan to make
the most of every opportunity across Sambro’s markets.  Sambro are now selling to Amazon and are refining
Sambro continues to develop its systems and processes in order to fulfil orders and support growth as efficiently
as possible.  They are continually reviewing ranges and categories as well as developing new products and IP in
Although Sambro has experienced a dip in performance which is reflective of the current trading environment,
based on the increased order book for the second half of the year we have valued the business at £11.8 million
which equates to par, down from £13.6 million at March 2018.
On 16 August 2016 the fund acquired Raymond Brown Minerals and Recycling Limited (“Raymond Brown”)
investing £23.99 million for a 72% equity stake.
In August 2017, the Fund acquired a further 3.1% of the ordinary share capital from the exiting CEO for £32,000,
The business comprises three distinct but complementary trading divisions – Quarry Products, which has a
number of sand and gravel quarries in Southern England, IBA (incinerator bottom ash) Processing which is one
of only 3 multi-site processors in the UK, and Waste which is a skip rental and materials recycling business.
Net debt includes HP of £5.4m against a budget of £7.1m
Overall the business was on budget for the first quarter.
Fortis had a positive start to the year processing some additional volumes which compensated for slightly lower
metal prices, influenced by China’s approach to scrap metal.  IBAA sales have been encouraging in the quarter
and IBAA from the A303 is now a Hampshire County Council approved sustainable product which will encourage
usage by builders and contractors within the county.
Elysian Capital II LP – Report of the Manager for the quarter ended 30 June 2018
For circulation to Limited Partners only
Quarries have performed well with turnover and EBITDA ahead of budget.  Binnegar was behind budget but this
was offset by better than plan sales at Roke and Brickworth.  Discussions are ongoing with a potential customer
for a significant volume of asphalt sand from Binnegar and Remix, who had a fire at their Avonmouth plant in
January and are anticipated to return in October.  All the necessary permits for tipping which had been in a
backlog at the Environment Agency have now been received, removing the need to ration, and tipping is slightly
ahead of budget for the quarter.
Within Waste, RoRo demand slowed as a major job was pushed back to June and skips were slightly behind
budget on volume and price. There have been a few large unbudgeted muckaway jobs by the grab lorries which
have reduced the impact of the skips performance.
Fortis, the IBA division, is finalising the detail for a new IBA contract for an incinerator under construction in Kent
and this is expected to be signed in the second quarter.  The EFW facility is due to be operational in the last
quarter of FY2019 with ash processed at A303 until the company has developed a new site in the South East.  A
location for this has been identified and an option is being negotiated with the landlord.  A new contract is being
negotiated to process 75,000 tonnes of IBAA for an existing EFW in the Midlands.  Processing will be on the EFW
site with a commencement date in Q3 FY19.  These contracts will have a material impact on the scale and
profitability of the Fortis business. The new Contract Manager has allowed the company to engage with other
customers around incinerators planned for 2020 and beyond.
Within quarries, a plant move at Binnegar, required due to the ending of a lease next to old quarry workings, is
underway. The new plant is on the same side of the main road as the current quarry area, reducing vehicle
movements. The Estates and Planning Department have completed a major exercise to identify potential
reserves within our existing counties of operation and immediately adjacent ones.  Discussions will focus on the
most attractive of these.  The current life of our reserves with planning is 8 years.
The company is starting to consider the timing of an exit from Waste given the greater opportunities for value
creation in the other parts of the business.  Management are developing a plan to replace the trommels at the
Material Recovery Facility which will deliver a cost saving but as importantly increase capacity by 15%.  New
contracts for the disposal of plasterboard and wood have been signed which will generate savings.
No further information has been received from Fareham Council regarding the promotion of the Rookery Farm
freehold site into the new housing plan.  Partner Group, part of Fastflow, are now looking at the potential of the
site for social housing and the likelihood of getting planning ahead of the publication of the housing plan.
Following the termination of Stuart Harris’ employment as CEO on 15 th  June 2017, Elysian engaged headhunters
to find a successor. We have now appointed a successor, Don Coates, who will commence on 1 st  September.
Don is an experienced CEO having worked in both public and private equity portfolio companies. He has run
capital projects, worked with the Environment Agency and been responsible for a large waste business, recycling
Raymond Brown has now been held for 22 months. Based on the increase in trailing 12 month EBITDA, the fund
has increased the value of the investment to £29.5 million from £24.6 million. This equates to a 20% uplift against
Elysian Capital II LP – Report of the Manager for the quarter ended 30 June 2018
For circulation to Limited Partners only
On 15 March 2017, Elysian acquired the Fastflow Group Limited for the headline price of £73.5 million. The total
equity investment was £31.8 million with Elysian retaining £23.8 million for a 40.4% equity stake and syndicating
the remaining £8 million which was made by Elysian’s Co-investor partners for a 13.5% equity stake.  Elysian
retained control over all key investment decisions with a combined institutional share of 53.9%.  The balance of
equity (46.1%) was held by the founder and management team.
On 28 February 2018, Fastflow Group acquired 100% of the share capital of Partner Group U.K. Limited (“Partner
Group”) for £7.0 million at an effective historic multiple of 3x. The company provides affordable housing to UK
housing associations and together with DWSS will help to expand Fastflow’s breadth of critical services to its
housing  association customers.  Post-acquisition Elysian retain a 39.89% equity stake and a combined 53.23%
share including co-investor holdings. The balance of equity (46.77%) is held by the founder and management
team.  This very small dilution arose from the issue of shares to the senior managers of the Partner Group. The
acquisition was funded by new bank debt of £6.5 million and existing cash resources.
Fastflow is a combination of three businesses that provide maintenance services to the owners of critical assets
– water, gas and social housing.  These businesses are Fastflow Pipeline Services (“FPS”), Fastflow Energy
Services (“FES”), DWSS and Partner, the Social Housing maintenance and house building businesses.
Results of the quarter to 30 June 2018:
*Net debt includes £6.2m of cash and £25.0m of senior loans after funding the Partner Group acquisition
Sales in the first quarter of £32.3 million were £1.1 million behind budget.  EBITDA for the quarter, excluding the
recent Partner acquisition, was £2.0 million, £0.5 million behind budget. This is primarily driven by the FES
division with a recent change in the pricing structure at a key customer adversely impacting margins.  Both FPS
and DWSS were ahead of prior year and slightly behind budget as a result of delays to projects which are
expected to commence later in the year.  Taking into account the earnings contribution of Partner, the enlarged
Group traded in line with the same period last year.
Operating cash conversion of the Group remains strong with another voluntary capital repayment of £4.0 million
from free trading cashflow made in June.  As a result, net debt was ahead of budget.
Partner Group is currently being professionalised with additional resource and support from the group function.
Elysian Capital II LP – Report of the Manager for the quarter ended 30 June 2018
For circulation to Limited Partners only
We are currently actively considering a number of acquisitions.
At 30 June 2018 based on a trailing twelve-month EBITDA for the enlarged Group with the pro forma inclusion
of the Partner acquisition, the Fund continues to value the investment at £31.0 million, which equates to a 30%
uplift against cost.  This represents an EBITDA multiple of 7.0x.
On 8 May 2017 the fund acquired Brand Addition Limited investing £21.5 million for an interest of 77.24%,
subject to a management performance ratchet.
The business designs, sources and distributes branded promotional products and merchandise for;
Blue chip corporate marketing programmes and branded merchandise using Brand Addition designed
and hosted in-house webshops (c.75% sales) e.g. JCB, Michelin, Maersk, Rolls Royce
Promotional products and packaging for FMCG clients to support consumer and gift-with-purchase
offerings e.g. Clarins, Jo Malone, Calvin Klein
The business operates in Manchester, London, Hagen (Germany), St Louis (USA), Dublin and Shanghai.
NOTES: Actual Net debt includes (£0.8m) of cash, £9.9m of debt fund loan and a £17.6m senior loan.
Sales of £19.4 million were behind budget of £21.3 million but up on the previous year by £0.8 million. The
variance against budget is primarily due to order phasing and, based on current order intake, we expect sales to
catch up in the second half of the year. The London, Manchester and Shanghai operations have continued to
perform satisfactorily in the second quarter with good order intakes. All divisions have performed a detailed
reforecast and management expect full year group EBITDA to be in line with budget.
The US business, in the hands of the new MD, is delivering good growth and we are looking closely at an
acquisition opportunity in the US.  Meanwhile we continue to review acquisition opportunities in other
territories with some potential targets identified.
Elysian Capital II LP – Report of the Manager for the quarter ended 30 June 2018

Brand Addition has now been held for 14 months. Based on the last twelve months EBITDA the fund values the
investment at £23.7 million which equates to a 10% uplift against cost.
On 25 May 2018 Elysian acquired Key Travel International Limited (“Key” or the “Company”) for £47.0 million,
investing £27.5 million for a 68.68% equity stake. The Company is the world’s leading niche travel management
Summary Financials for the quarter to 30 June 2018:
The Company services the not-for profit sector across 3 sub-sectors – education, humanitarian and faith. Helping
customers make significant savings, manage traveller welfare and overcome the complexities of their unique
travel requirements. The nature of the customers combined with the destinations involved and level of bespoke
service lend themselves to a specialist provider.
The business is headquartered in the UK but also has operations in Central Europe and the US.
Key’s growth strategy is to expand its share of wallet from existing customers across its segments and extend its
geographical footprint into Europe and in particular the US, the world’s largest travel market.  In addition where
Key can make a stepped-change to its overseas operations via acquisition.
For the 9 months year to date the Company is on-plan and remains confident of achieving its year end outturn
of £4.3 million EBITDA, on a normalised basis.
Saad Hammad, CEO, is supported by Alex Davis, CFO, and an experienced senior management team. The
Company is chaired by Elysian Operating Partner Tom Falcon, who is joined on the Board by Ken Terry and Jack
In accordance with industry guidelines, the Fund holds the investment at cost.
During the quarter Elysian reviewed 27 new deals which includes a number of potential bolt on opportunities
for exiting portfolio companies.  The target remains to complete at least one further platform deal in 2018.

In accordance with the Limited Partnership Agreement the Priority Profit Share (PPS) is payable six monthly in
advance on 31 December and 30 June.  During the Investment Period the annual PPS will be equal to 2% of
Limited Partner Commitments reduced by 100% for fees received by the Manager / General Partner in the prior
accounting period.   Following the end of the Investment Period the PPS is calculated at 2% per annum of the
aggregate acquisition cost of investments held by the Partnership reduced by the acquisition cost of all
investments made by the Partnership which have been fully written off, reduced by 100% for fees received by
the Manager / General Partner.  In any period if the fees to be offset are greater than the value of the PPS any
excess will be carried forward to the next period.
